le="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/sw1VjFZ</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[LogicDude]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Yes</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/jlIezEA</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/2FKTObH.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/jlIezEA</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[TheWhatever666]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>LAPD confronted over ICE restraining order</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/3k6NyMw</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/3PsZMJP.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>William Gude from Film the Police LA.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/3k6NyMw</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[AnonymousMockingjay]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Mr. Rogers Stand Firm</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/gmrwKjD</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/24rrCFN.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Fred Rogers never lent his name to commercial products, so in 1985, when Burger King released a commercial featuring an actor dressed like him under the name “Mister Rodney,” he was deeply troubled. Though the ad was meant as light-hearted parody, Rogers feared it might confuse children who trusted and identified with his television persona. “To have someone who looks like me doing a commercial is very confusing for children,” he explained. He personally contacted Don Dempsey, Burger King’s Senior Vice President, who quickly agreed to pull the ad. Despite a $150,000 investment, the commercial only aired a handful of times before being removed. “Mister Rogers is one guy you don’t want to mess with,” Dempsey later admitted. “As beloved as he is, it just wasn’t worth it.”

Rogers took misrepresentation seriously—especially when it risked misleading children or compromising the values he spent his life nurturing. When Johnny Carson spoofed him in a sketch titled “Mister Rambo’s Neighborhood” on The Tonight Show, Rogers voiced his disappointment. Carson responded with a public apology, acknowledging that the parody may have gone too far. Still, Rogers wasn’t opposed to all satire. He famously appreciated Eddie Murphy’s “Mister Robinson’s Neighborhood” on Saturday Night Live, a gritty, streetwise take on his own show. He understood the humor and recognized the sketch was aimed at an adult audience during a late-night slot, where children were unlikely to see it.

But some uses of his image went too far. In 1998, Rogers was outraged when a Texas retailer began selling T-shirts featuring a doctored photo of him holding a gun, paired with the phrase, “Welcome to my ’hood.” This time, he wasn’t just disappointed—he was furious. Rather than simply requesting the shirts be pulled from shelves, he demanded that every copy be destroyed. Though he rarely displayed anger in public, Rogers was firm when it came to defending the principles he stood for.

His influence extended well beyond children’s television. In the early 1980s, as the entertainment industry pushed back against home video recording, Rogers testified before the U.S. Supreme Court in support of VCRs. While many in television feared lost revenue, Rogers believed that allowing parents to record his show encouraged learning and brought families together. His calm, heartfelt testimony made a deep impression. The Court ruled in favor of home recording, citing Rogers’ remarks in their decision—a quiet but pivotal moment that helped shape the future of media, from VHS tapes to modern streaming.

Though known for his gentle demeanor, Fred Rogers was never passive. He stood firm when it mattered—whether confronting corporations, challenging tasteless parodies, or influencing national policy. At the heart of it all was a steadfast commitment to children and their emotional well-being. His legacy is a powerful reminder that kindness is not weakness, and that quiet conviction can leave a lasting mark. As he always reminded his viewers, “You made this a special day just by being you. 

Credit:  University of life</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/gmrwKjD</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[TheTaoofRob]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Time to cut some onions</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/0kDAKjQ</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/d3wGrCV.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Three years after Jorge went missing, Giorgi Berejiani's search ended in joy. a local business spotted a dog matching Jorge's description. Despite being tagged as a stray, Berejiani rushed to confirm it was his beloved pet. The reunion was emotional, with both Jorge and Giorgi overwhelmed with happiness.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/DlprRUv.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The yellow ear tag on Jorge indicates he was captured as a stray by animal control in Tbilisi, Georgia, then vaccinated, sterilized, and released as part of a humane population management program. It's common for street dogs there to avoid repeated captures.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/RTVrPhX.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/0kDAKjQ</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[LogicDude]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Trump and the GOP are Segregationists. It is what fits the best.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/c7vWPc4</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/j3Ap6g7.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>They sound like Nazi's, but the reason for that is the history of the USA is very unequal and... Authoritarian through the 1890s period to the reforms.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/kUzmVLc.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>https://www.history.com/articles/how-the-nazis-were-inspired-by-jim-crow</div></div>]]></description>